iple refugee regimes govern the lives of forced migrants simultaneously but in an often conflicting way. As a mechanism of inclusion/exclusion, they tend to engender the violence they sought to dissipate. Protection and control channel agency through mechanisms of either tutelage and victimisation or criminalisation. This book contrasts multiple groups of refugees and refugee regimes, revealing the inherent coercive violence of refugee regimes, from displacement and expulsion, to stereotypification and exclusion in host countries, and academic knowledge essentialisation. This violence is international, national, society-based, internalised, and embodied - and it urgently needs due scholarly attention.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 4aCultural Anthropology. 4aMigration. 4aRefugee Studies. 4aViolence. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aCultural Anthropology.  aMigration.  aRefugee Studies.  aViolence.1 aAlves de Souza, Mirian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauer-Amin, Sabine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauer-Amin, Sabine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBöge, Rozalie E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriese, Heidrun, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiritli Nygren, Katarina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMokre, Monika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMonsutti, Alessandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNyhlén, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchiocchet, Leonardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchiocchet, Leonar